text.tspan: The sample size represents 55% (121) female students, 44.5% (98) male students, and
0.5% (1) students who preferred not to disclose their gender. 57.3% (126) of the respondents
were living in a COVID-19 red zone (hotspot), while 22.3% (49) students and 20.55% (45)
students were living in a COVID-19 yellow and a COVID-19 green zone, respectively.
Furthermore, 19.5% (43) of the respondents scored between 91%-100% in the previous grade,
while 37.3% (82), 28.2% (62), and 15% (33) of students scored between 81%-90%, 71%-80%,
and below 71%, respectively, in their previous grades.
Findings and Discussion
Stressors
Stress from Family
58.6% of the students did not express any stress from family members whatsoever during
the nationwide COVID-19 lockdown. However, prominent family stressors included high
expectations in examinations and parental limits on time spent in daily activities (Table 1).
Misunderstandings between parents and children were also observed as a culprit for stress among
students; one school boarder mentioned unnecessary distractions at home and reduced focus on
studies due to the presence of family members. Three students admitted to feeling constant stress
because their parents tried to make them use their "free" time to study. When asked how the
COVID-19 lockdown has affected student stress emanating from family members in comparison
to pre-lockdown conditions, the 5-point Likert scale analysis (Table 2) revealed a slight increase
